g.desc: Single Responsibility Principle (SRP) Each software module sh...

text.tspan: Each software module should have one and only one reason

g.title: Rectangle.43
g.desc: Less likely to break existing code unrelated to the change
g.text: Less likely to break existing code unrelated to the change

g.title: Rectangle.15
g.desc: Identify affects of changes easier and quicker
g.text: Identify affects of changes easier and quicker

g.title: Folded Corner.59
g.desc: A module containing multiple responsibilities, will have mult...

g.text: A module containing multiple responsibilities, will have multiple reasons to change. When introducing new functionality in such a module, there is a higher risk that other responsibilities, unrelated to the change, will be affected.

g.title: Folded Corner.25
g.desc: Multiple modules, all performing a single responsibility, is ...

g.text: Multiple modules, all performing a single responsibility, is easier to read and understand in comparison to a monolithic, ‘god’ class fulfilling multiple responsibilities. Easy understandable code will enhance design, reduce bugs and time spend on a change or addition.

g.title: Folded Corner
g.desc: It is easier to ‘pin-point’ out what might be the functional ...

g.text: It is easier to ‘pin-point’ out what might be the functional affect of changing a module when it only performs a single responsibility, because code is more separated. This will improve time estimates, design and overcome bugs.

g.title: Folded Corner.62
g.desc: A developer is able to work more frequently with less interfe...

g.text: A developer is able to work more frequently with less interference of other developers, when a system is more distributed. This will result in less conflicts when using a version control system.

g.title: Rectangle.34
g.desc: Simplify reuse of modules in other parts of the system
g.text: Simplify reuse of modules in other parts of the system

g.title: Folded Corner.65
g.desc: Modules which have a single responsibility and only one reaso...

g.text: Modules which have a single responsibility and only one reason to change can be re-used more frequently in other projects/parts of the system. This is because it is more likely to ‘fit’ a particular use-case than a monolith / ‘god’ module. This will result in less development time.

g.title: Folded Corner.54
g.desc: Testing a module which only fulfills a single responsibility ...

g.text: Testing a module which only fulfills a single responsibility will be easier and quicker to test, because it contains less use-cases. Testing our software easier and quicker means we can identify the root cause of failures earlier and our problem ‘window’ is minimized to a single responsible unit.

g.title: Rectangle.85
g.desc: Enhance identification of use and edge cases
g.text: Enhance identification of use and edge cases

g.title: Folded Corner.87
g.desc: A module that fulfills a single responsibility makes it easie...

g.text: A module that fulfills a single responsibility makes it easier to comprehend the edge and ‘normal’ test cases, because there is more overview in contrast to a monolithic module. This will improve test coverage and thus minimize bugs.

g.title: Folded Corner.99
g.desc: The ‘strength’ of the relationships between the internals of ...

g.text: The ‘strength’ of the relationships between the internals of a module determine its single responsibility ‘level’. If there is a weak level of cohesion it means that the module contains unrelated functionality and thus has multiple reasons to change.

g.title: Folded Corner.102
g.desc: The ‘weakness’ of relationships towards other modules determi...

g.text: The ‘weakness’ of relationships towards other modules determine the single responsibility of a module. If a module has a ‘strong’ relation towards another module the chance that both modules need to change simultaneously becomes higher. Two modules changing simultaneously means both modules have not one reason to change, but multiple.

g.title: Folded Corner.113
g.desc: A module is responsible for a specific task and the result of...

g.text: A module is responsible for a specific task and the result of that task may be worked with by other entities. A module may not expose all it’s internals, because this would mean that the responsibility of its task could shift to other modules. ‘Bad’ encapsulation can enlarge the risk of tight coupling.

g.title: Folded Corner.118
g.desc: Module A contains two responsibilities, A1 and A2. Module B d...

g.text: Module A contains two responsibilities, A1 and A2. Module B depends on A1 and module C on A2. When A1 changes both B and C need to recompile. Separating the responsibilities of A into two separate modules will only make B recompile when A1 changes and C when A2 changes. This will result in less recompilation time.
